Author: jason#9686
Content:
just found a little gotcha: It is very important that your [0][0] tuple has an operation of *None*! check50 passes with other values there, but when using flask run , application.py will fail with an index out of bounds error :  application.py contains a loop where that None in the [0][0] position is the end condition.  

In the walkthrough (essential watching) there is what I thought was a throwaway comment with lots of hand waving at  11:00 in https://youtu.be/YTO92oVoYwA?list=PLhQjrBD2T381-bOArPXzvlXpovpdBhrZ3&t=667 " for matrix[0][0] there was no operation that needed to be done there, so just store None for the Operation in that case"  perhaps Brian could have said, "store None for the operation at [0][0]  otherwise the code we've written to display operations will fail at run time..."  

Can we add a check50 test for this?

Author: Maarten#1004
Content: If I understand correctly (and I'm in no way an expert) DP is about being smart and reusing answers you've already created in new situations, in such a way that you don't have to start from scratch every time. For example: in the DP lecture there first is the part about the edit distance and after that prof. Brown continues to image compositing / seam carving. There you again see the ideas which where already thought of in the edit distance but applied in very different way (calculate the nearest (lowest costing) color switch, etc.). So the result of the overlapping idea of calculating the costs between one thing and another (text, pixels) is already saved and doesn't need to be thought out again, it can be used now as a solved subproblem of a bigger problem (how to resize an image in the best way possible / glue to pictures together).

Author: Maarten#1004
Content: And for Levenshtein: just check the top few results on Google I suppose üòÉ been a few weeks back and didn't save the articles that were most helpful to me.

Author: bug#5428
Content: Yeah, I understand the purpose of dynamic programming quite well. But I don't understand if it's just a tweak you have to apply to previously created algorithms or if you just get rid of  the whole original algorithm and just create a totally different one using Dynamic Programming.

Author: bug#5428
Content: For example, the edit distance problem is complex, because you need to consider all the possible ways you can re-arrange a string X to turn it into a string Y (without actually doing it), and from all those possible ways you have to simulate the path in which you get the least amount of changes, i.e. the smallest cost.

Author: bug#5428
Content: With this recursive approach to edit distance, which I found in 90% of the searches I've done, you end up going through every possible scenario of the process in which string X can be transformed into a string Y, however I understand there are some "sub-paths" that repeat many times, especially for long strings, and so we create a data structure to store those answers without making our program calculate these again if that "sub-path" has already been taken.

Author: Maarten#1004
Content: It will probably depend on the situation I suppose, for the examples given the underlying ideas are similar but the codes are definitly not identical. Don't know if I understand you correctly, but for the edit distance algorithm we need you can fill out the first row and column with only the knowledge of the length of the string. The rest of the matrix will differ from word to word. The way how these calculations are made are always the same though.

Author: puzzledbytheweb#8614
Content:
do this:
```
list = (delete, insert, sub) # Create a list to check its index later
minimum =  min(list) # which gives you the minimum int value of those 3. Value to store in the 0th element
minimum_index = list.index(minimum) # which compares a value (minimum in this case)  to a list's elements (list(delete, insert, sub)) and retrieves its index (order of apearance)

```

        elif min(delete, insert, sub) == sub:
            operation = "S"

        matrix[i][j] = min(delete, insert, sub), operation``

Content: `return [list]` returns a list that contains `list`

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: `return list` returns `list` itself.

Content: so if `list` is a list, you'd get a list containing one list if you did `return [list]`

Author: Bhau#9899
Content: Could anyone explain what this statement " print(d[len(file1)][len(file2)][0]) "does in similarities/more. I know d is the fuction that calculates edit distance but what are the other values there for

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: so that is printing the final score (ie, the value in the last row / last column)

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: let's say you were calculating the score for a change from "boat" to "cat".  If you were to print `d` (which is the array that is returned), it would look like this: ```[[(0, None), (1, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>), (2, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], [(1, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (1, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>), (2, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], [(2, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], [(3, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (3, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], [(4, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (4, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (3, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>)]]```

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content:
let's format that a bit: ```
[[(0, None), (1, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>), (2, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], 
[(1, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (1, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>), (2, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], 
[(2, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], 
[(3, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (3, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>), (3, <Operation.INSERTED: 2>)], 
[(4, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (4, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (3, <Operation.DELETED: 1>), (2, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>)]]```

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: so len(file1) is 4 and len(file2) is 3, so  `d[4][3]` is `(2, <Operation.SUBSTITUTED: 3>)`  so `d[4][3][0]` is 2

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: and 2 is the distance from "boat" to "cat" as shown in the staff solution:

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: if you have 2 files, one with the word "boat" and one with the word "cat" and run `./score boat.txt cat.txt` it will return 2.

Author: Fer#1196
Content: @XtratoS , Your logic is right, i had the same issue, but i think that the explanation is the following.  Some of the axioms of the algorithm are:  Deletion is moving down a square, Insertion is moving right and Substitution is moving diagonal. You have to follow those rules so that the logic of finding the optimal solution via this table works.  Substitution is always diagonal, but it has two options; one is just coping what you had, and two substituting the character.

    substring = []

Author: agucova#3597
Content: With the condition in the if having `i + 1 % n` because, as I understand it, i starts with 0 through the iterations, so I needed to add one in order to get it to match n, the number of characters after it should split the substring.

Author: agucova#3597
Content: That, is, if we are in the 8th character, i would be 7. And if n is 4, `i + 1 % n` should be equal to 0, since (7 + 1) modulo 8 should be 0.

Author: agucova#3597
Content: But, the code only works if the condition is `i % n == 0` instead.

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: `i + 1 % n == 0`   modulo takes precedence, so you probably aren't getting what you expect

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: that's equivalent to `i + (1%n)`

def main():

    f.close()

if __name__ == "__main__":

```

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: so if you have a string `words` like "Here's a sentence. And here's another sentence.  This one is also a sentence?  Yes!"   then `sent_tokenize(words)` would return this list: `["Here's a sentence.",  "And here's another sentence.",   "This one is also a sentence? ", Yes!" ]`

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: so the idea is that you tokenize the two strings you are given, and return the ones in the list that are in common.  (you might look at python `set`s for that)

The compare program has this ```python
    # Output matches, sorted from longest to shortest, with line endings escaped
    for match in sorted(matches, key=len, reverse=True):
        print(match.replace("\n", "\\n").replace("\r", "\\r"))
```  which means that when you run your version, you'll see the `\n` in the output, rather than it being interpreted as a newline.   The staff version doesn't have that, so the newlines are interpreted.  That means you may see something like this:  ```
defg
g\nhi
efg\n
```  vs staff  ```
defg
g
ni
efg

```   with substrings of length 4

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content:
the maximum number of substrings you can have is limited by the length of the string and then length of the substring.  For example, if you have a string of length 6 and substring of length 4  ```
123456```   can give you 3 substrings:
```
1234
2345
3456  
```

    l2 = re.findall(r'.+\.\s', b)

    l = []
    for s in l1:
        if s in l2 and s not in l:
            l.append(s)
    return l```||
